@NODE "mail_2" " Re: .txt files to strings, and packing. "
From: David McMinn <dave@...>
Date: 10-12-02 23:18:57
Subject: @{b}Re: .txt files to strings, and packing.@{ub}

> and now I need something like it
> for "mission text", and other things in a game.
> so I would really like some advice,
> because I don't want to fill my code with
> these texts.

DIm mission_text.s(100)
If ReadFile(0, "the name of the mission text file")
    FileInput 0
    i = 0
    While Not Eof(0)
        ; This allows up to 256 characters per line. They must be Amiga
        ; style line endings (CR), not Windows style (CRLF)
        mission_text(i) = Edit$(256)
        i=i+1
    Wend
    PopInput
    CloseFile 0
EndIf

> also, to not let files be "free for view"
> I pondered about whatever packing methods
> is easiest to use when I need to edit
> the files frequently. 

The simplest method is to use the Cipher$ command. You would need to save your text files 
using the Cipher$ command (something like this):

DIm mission_text.s(100)
If WriteFile(0, "the name of the plain text mission text file")
    FileOutput 0
    For i=0 To number_of_lines_in_mission_text
		NPrint Cipher$(mission_text(i)
    Next
    PopOutput
    CloseFile 0
EndIf


And now your code to read these texts in could be something like this:

DIm mission_text.s(100)
If ReadFile(0, "the name of the mission text file")
    FileInput 0
    i = 0
    While Not Eof(0)
        ; This allows up to 256 characters per line. They must be Amiga
        ; style line endings (CR), not Windows style (CRLF)
        mission_text(i) = Cipher$(Edit$(256))
        i=i+1
    Wend
    PopInput
    CloseFile 0
EndIf


However, the Cipher$ is not very secure, which you can see from the source code of the 
ElmoreDosLib. It might mean normal users cannot see your text but if someone is determined 
to get it they might work it out. Of course, there is also no compression with Cipher$


Another option would be to use powerpacker (there are some functions on Aminet to show you 
how to use PowerPacker in Blitz) or another compression library (IIRC there were some 
compression libraries that RWE released as part of the Blitz Support Suite). The 
disadvantage here is that the file format will give away the encoding of your files and so 
someone would need to simply use the decompression tool for that format to read your texts.


Obviously you could combine the two methods (encoding and compression) for more security.

