@NODE "mail_88" " Re: max shape number "
From: David McMinn <dave@...>
Date: 10-27-02 23:25:10
Subject: @{b}Re: max shape number@{ub}


> > So for 8 bitplanes you need read the maskbits that guigfx generate and
> > make 8 bits out of it or better fix guigfx

> Are you sure ? Blitzshapes (designed for OCS/AGA) use a mask (=cookie)
> of only one bitplane.

Interleaved bitmaps (default type allocated on OS3.0) are different.

If you do not know, they are allocated so that the layout of the bitmap looks like this (for a 
bitmap with 3 bitplanes and 4 lines):

Plane 0 Line 0
Plane 1 Line 0
Plane 2 Line 0
Plane 0 Line 1
Plane 1 Line 1
Plane 2 Line 1
Plane 0 Line 2
Plane 1 Line 2
Plane 2 Line 2
Plane 0 Line 3
Plane 1 Line 3
Plane 2 Line 3

A normal bitmap looks like this BTW:

Plane 0 Line 0
Plane 0 Line 1
Plane 0 Line 2
Plane 0 Line 3
Plane 1 Line 0
Plane 1 Line 1
Plane 1 Line 2
Plane 1 Line 3
Plane 2 Line 0
Plane 2 Line 1
Plane 2 Line 2
Plane 2 Line 3

Normally you can create a 1 bitplane mask, which has the same size as a single bitplane from 
the bitmap, and apply it to the three separate blits of planes 0, 1 and 2. However, with 
interleaved bitmaps you cannot create the same single bitplane mask (or if you do, you must 
stretch it by the depth). This allows you to blit an image using one blit instead of one for 
each plane.

